Black Rome.” These novels show differing visions of revolution, black community, femininity, sexuality, and captivity. They skillfully reveal how events preceding the UNESCO Decade of Afro-Descent (2015–2024) alter our understanding of Afro-⁠Latin America as it gains increased visibility. Published by Bucknell University Press. Distributed worldwide by Rutgers University Press.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAfrican diaspora in literature. 0aLatin American literaturexBlack authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aLatin American literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLatin American literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aBlack Atlantic, Afrodescendente, Afro-Latin America, Afrofuturism, Muntu, Latin American Studies, Literature, Culture, African American Studies, Race, Ethnic Studies, Cultural Studies, Literary Studies, Caribbean, Latin American, Comparative Literature, African diaspora studies, Manuel Zapata Olivella, Ana Maria Gonçalves Black Rome.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021 Englishz978311075412408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021z9783110753899oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073913840uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978168448190340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781684481903423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781684481903/original  a978-3-11-073913-8  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075412-4  EBOOK P